[2
From: Angela M. Lee <finchley@qis.net>
Data: 7 Oct 2001
Source: Associated Press [edited
<http://ap.tbo.com/ap/florida/MGA7KTNCJSC.html>

5 People Treated After Receive Envelope With Mystery Powder
------------------------------------------------------------
HIALEAH, Fla. (AP) -- 5 people were hospitalized Sunday after they opened 2
manila envelopes containing a mysterious white powder, rescue officials
said. One person at an apartment complex in this Miami suburb was taken to
the hospital Sunday after opening an envelope containing the powder,
Hialeah Fire-Rescue Department officials said. The person's condition was
not immediately available.
That came one day after 4 people at a house 20 blocks [?away opened an
envelope containing an apparently identical powder. 3 of the 4 occupants of
the house -- a 72-year-old man, his 72-year-old sister-in-law, his
36-year-old daughter and a 70-year-old woman -- developed low-grade fevers
after they arrived Sunday at Palm Springs General Hospital, said Stanley
Stark, a fire-rescue spokesman. He did not know which.
The man was going through the home's mail Saturday afternoon when he opened
the business-size envelope containing the powder. The home's occupants
initially did not think much of the substance, but their fears it could be
something harmful grew overnight and they alerted authorities Sunday
morning, Stark said. The FBI and a hazardous materials team from Hialeah
Fire-Rescue quarantined the one-story home, taking the mail and the
clothing the occupants wore at the time the envelope was opened, Stark said.
Neighbors on both sides of the home, who had previously been told not to go
outside, were allowed to leave. Entry to the block, which had not been
permitted earlier, was granted. It was unclear what the powder was and why
the family received a letter containing an unknown substance, Stark said.
The FBI was hoping to complete preliminary testing of the substance late
Sunday.
--
