[3
Date: 5 Oct 2001 23:12:04 -0500
From: Peters, Clarence J. <cjpeters@UTMB.EDU>

I would point out the importance of pathological exam in the emerging
infections / BT work in general. In this particular case, it may well tell
us the portal of entry and how the meningeal "cardinal's cap" which is
expected may have come about.
A few years ago pathological exam in the USSR provided definitive proof of
the existence of inhalation anthrax following the Sverdlovsk incident. In
fact the early literature of anthrax has lots of good information on early
events in the infection based on finding spores and sporulation in critical
areas of the lung at critical times. It is also worth reflecting that when
you look, you find.
I do not want to suggest that a deep intelligence and epidemiological
investigation of this case should not be undertaken -- clearly this is a
high priority. I would like to add that more awareness of some of the less
well-appreciated infectious diseases will give us lots of new info on
previously under-recognized conditions, stress the limited resources of the
public health system, and generally improve our understanding of infectious
disease.
---
CJ Peters
Univ. Texas Medical Branch
Galveston TX
<cjpeters@UTMB.EDU>
[To which I can only add, "Amen." Thanks CJ. - Mod.MHJ
